		<dc:title id="title">Short Fiction</dc:title>
		<meta property="file-as" refines="#title">Short Fiction</meta>
		<dc:subject id="subject-1">Japan -- Social life and customs -- Fiction</dc:subject>
		<meta property="authority" refines="#subject-1">LCHS</meta>
		<meta property="term" refines="#subject-1">Unknown</meta>
		<dc:subject id="subject-2">Short stories, Japanese -- Translations into English</dc:subject>
		<meta property="authority" refines="#subject-2">LCHS</meta>
		<meta property="term" refines="#subject-2">Unknown</meta>
		<meta property="se:subject">Fiction</meta>
		<meta property="se:subject">Shorts</meta>
		<meta property="se:is-a-collection">true</meta>
		<dc:description id="description">A collection of short fiction by Akutagawa Ryūnosuke, ordered by date of publication.</dc:description>
		<meta id="long-description" property="se:long-description" refines="#description">
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://standardebooks.org/ebooks/akutagawa-ryunosuke"&gt;Akutagawa Ryūnosuke&lt;/a&gt; was a respected author in pre-war Japan; being well-read in several topics and having received a westernized education, his work blends traditional themes os Japanese culture with Western concepts. His almost 200 stories deal with a variety of themes and concepts; “The Nose” is a tale about vanity and perception of one’s image, “Rashōmon” deals with morality in the face of necessity, “The Story of a Fallen Head” is an anti-war story. Akutagawa often ends his stories with a reflection related to the plot, spoken either by one character to another or by the narrator to the reader.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Most of his fiction hasn’t been translated into English. Collected here are the few stories believed to have lapsed into public domain.&lt;/p&gt;
		</meta>
		<dc:language>en-US</dc:language>
		<!-- "The Ball," "Lice," "Mōri Sensei," "Rashōmon," "The Badger," "The Handkerchief," "The Nose," "The Pipe," "The Spider's Thread," "The Wine Worm" and "Tobacco and the Devil"-->
